        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>Where it shines.</strong> Deep pedigree management, COI and relatedness analysis, and the ability to maintain a clean multi-generation database across many animals. Strong for breed clubs and breeders who treat the database itself as the deliverable.</p>
        <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Where it may fall short for operational breeders.</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3 space-y-2">
          <li>The product's center of gravity is records and pedigree, not operational workflow. Heat cycle and progesterone-timing workflows do not appear to be primary emphases.</li>
          <li>Buyer-facing portal, waitlist, deposit, contract, and marketplace tooling do not appear to be the product's focus.</li>
          <li>The interface and user experience reflect the product's heritage as a records database rather than a modern mobile-first operations tool.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed"><strong>Who should look here first.</strong> Breeders and clubs whose work is fundamentally pedigree- and records-driven, not those running an end-to-end puppy program.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Kintraks -->
      <div id="kintraks" class="mb-12 pt-8 border-t border-gray-200 scroll-mt-24">
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3">Kintraks</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>Best suited for:</strong> Established breeders who want a long-running, traditional records-and-pedigree tool with registry export features.</p>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>Public positioning.</strong> Kintraks is a long-established breeder records product with pedigree, breeding records, and registration support. It targets breeders who want a comprehensive records system from a vendor that has been in the category for a long time.</p>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>Where it shines.</strong> Maturity. The product has had years to round out its records and pedigree features, and it is familiar to breeders who have used desktop-style breeder software before.</p>
        <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Where it may fall short for operational breeders.</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3 space-y-2">
          <li>The product's heritage and public positioning emphasize records and pedigree over modern workflow tooling like progesterone timing, integrated waitlist management, buyer portals, and marketplace presence.</li>
          <li>User experience reflects the product's age. Breeders coming from modern SaaS may find the workflow patterns dated.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed"><strong>Who should look here first.</strong> Breeders whose current pain is "I need a real records system" rather than "I need to run my whole program in one place."</p>
      </div>

      <!-- PedFast -->
      <div id="pedfast" class="mb-12 pt-8 border-t border-gray-200 scroll-mt-24">
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3">PedFast</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>Best suited for:</strong> Breed clubs, pedigree-heavy breeders, and anyone whose primary deliverable is a printed or digital pedigree.</p>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>Public positioning.</strong> PedFast publicly positions itself around pedigree generation: building, formatting, and printing pedigrees, primarily on a Windows desktop workflow.</p>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>Where it shines.</strong> Pedigree work. If your output is pedigrees (for buyers, breed clubs, or registries) a focused pedigree tool will produce cleaner results than a general operations tool that also prints pedigrees.</p>
        <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Where it may fall short for operational breeders.</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3 space-y-2">
          <li>Pedigrees are one part of running a program. Heat cycle tracking, progesterone timing, litter operations, waitlists, contracts, deposits, and buyer portals are not the product's focus.</li>
          <li>A desktop-leaning workflow is at odds with how most breeders actually run their day (phone in hand, in the whelping area or at a show).</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed"><strong>Who should look here first.</strong> Breeders whose biggest job is pedigree production, not program operations.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Breed Ledger -->
      <div id="breed-ledger" class="mb-12 pt-8 border-t border-gray-200 scroll-mt-24">
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3">Breed Ledger</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>Best suited for:</strong> Breeders who want a breeder website, a cross-breeder pedigree database, and species-aware genetics in one tool, on a free-to-start plan, across dogs, cats, reptiles, and other species.</p>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>Public positioning.</strong> Breed Ledger (breedledger.co) is built by Dusty, a working multi-species breeder who also built ReptiDex. It pairs a website builder (Classic, Modern, and Minimal templates, subdomain immediately, custom domain and SSL on paid plans) with a pedigree database, a genetics engine, a buyer waitlist, and a buyer-facing directory. Pricing is a Free plan (up to 10 animals, 3-generation pedigrees, subdomain, directory listing, inquiry form), Starter at $29/mo (up to 50 animals, custom domain, genetics predictions, 5-generation pedigrees, waitlists, contracts), and Professional at $49/mo (unlimited animals, unlimited pedigree depth, advanced analytics). Annual billing saves two months. Separate club and registry plans start higher for membership, dues, and stud-book work. An optional 0.5% fee applies only when you use Breed Ledger's own payment processing. The product is live in production and actively developed.</p>
        <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Where it shines.</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3 space-y-2">
          <li>Website builder and breeder records in one place, so your public site and your pedigree data are not two separate tools.</li>
          <li>Species-aware genetics rather than a generic pet CMS. It tracks the traits a species actually needs (for reptiles, that includes het status, albino, line-bred lines, polygenic color, and sex-linked traits) and offers genetics predictions on paid tiers.</li>
          <li>Visual multi-generation pedigrees where you can click any sire or dam to drill in, with cross-breeder links that connect partner programs.</li>
          <li>Waitlists that tie to specific animals or trait combinations, with deposits routing to selected pups and e-signed contracts.</li>
          <li>A buyer-facing directory where prospective buyers browse by species and region and link out to each breeder's own site.</li>
          <li>A genuinely free entry plan, which is unusual in this category, plus free migration help from existing platforms.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Where BreederHQ pulls ahead.</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3 space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Canine-specific reproduction workflow.</strong> Multi-point progesterone timing, AI and frozen-semen documentation, and heat-cycle tracking are the center of BreederHQ. Breed Ledger's public emphasis is website, pedigree, and genetics, not progesterone-driven breeding timing.</li>
          <li><strong>No OFA Sync or CHIC Readiness.</strong> Breed Ledger does not publicly offer automatic OFA result pulls or breed-specific CHIC health-test planning.</li>
          <li><strong>No Volhard PAT, Gun Dog Aptitude, or Scout AI document extraction.</strong> Those are BreederHQ features that do not appear in Breed Ledger's public materials.</li>
          <li><strong>Directory rather than a listing marketplace.</strong> Breed Ledger's directory sends buyers to individual breeder sites; BreederHQ's marketplace at marketplace.breederhq.com is a listing marketplace where buyers search by available animal.</li>
          <li><strong>Web-based, no native mobile app.</strong> BreederHQ ships iOS and Android apps for whelping nights and shows; Breed Ledger is responsive web only based on its public site.</li>
          <li><strong>Solo-founder product with no independent reviews yet.</strong> Breed Ledger does not have Capterra or G2 reviews at this stage, so verify the fit against your own program with the free plan before committing.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed"><strong>Honest verdict.</strong> If your biggest need is a breeder website plus a cross-breeder pedigree database and species-aware genetics, and you like the idea of starting free and paying $29/mo or $49/mo as you grow, Breed Ledger is a genuinely interesting option, especially for morph-driven species like reptiles. If you run a working dog program where progesterone timing, OFA Sync, temperament testing, a per-buyer portal, and a native mobile app matter, BreederHQ is built around that operational core in a way Breed Ledger's public positioning is not.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- GoodDog -->
      <div class="mb-4 pt-8 border-t border-gray-200">
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3">GoodDog <span class="text-gray-500 font-normal text-base">(marketplace context only)</span></h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
          GoodDog is not breeder operations software. It is a buyer-facing marketplace where prospective puppy buyers discover breeders, plus a directory-style breeder profile. It belongs in this comparison only so the distinction stays clean.
        </p>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>What GoodDog is for.</strong> Helping buyers find breeders, and giving breeders a curated directory presence.</p>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>What GoodDog is not for.</strong> Running your program. Heat cycle tracking, progesterone timing, litter records, waitlists, contracts, deposits, and your day-to-day operational work all live somewhere else.</p>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed"><strong>How it relates to BreederHQ.</strong> BreederHQ is operations and marketplace in one system. The program records, the buyer pipeline, and a public listing presence at marketplace.breederhq.com all live in the same place. If you are already on GoodDog, you do not have to leave it. But GoodDog by itself does not replace breeder operations software.</p>
      </div>
